What is Playwright?

Answer

Playwright is an open-source end-to-end automation framework developed by Microsoft. 
It supports Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit browsers and allows cross-browser testing and Parallel execution

"Q1. Why Playwright over Selenium?"
Answer
Faster execution
Auto-wait mechanism
Supports multiple tabs/windows easily
Better handling of modern applications
Built-in API testing
Network interception support
Parallel execution built-in
Better stability compared to Selenium
Follow-up

“What is auto-wait?”

Answer

Playwright automatically waits for:

element visibility
stability
enabled state
attached to DOM

before performing actions.

Example:
await page.locator('#login').click();


"Q3. What browsers does Playwright support?"
Answer
Chromium
Firefox
WebKit

Also supports:

Chrome
Edge

"Q4. Explain Playwright architecture."
Answer

Playwright communicates directly with browser engines using browser protocols instead of WebDriver.

Architecture:
Test Script → Playwright API → Browser Engine


"Q6. What are locators in Playwright?"
Answer

Locators are Playwright’s recommended way to find elements.

Example:
page.locator('#username')


"Q7. Which locator strategy is best?"
{User facing locators}
Best Order

getByRole()
getByLabel()
getByText()
data-testid
CSS/XPath

Example:
page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Login' })


"Q8. Difference between locator() and $()"
 or "Difference between locator and elementHandle?"
{Difference: page.locator() vs page.$()}

page.$()
Returns an ElementHandle
Finds the element immediately
If the element changes later, the handle may become stale
Does not auto-wait
Older API style
Usually discouraged in modern Playwright

Example:
const btn = await page.$('#login');
await btn.click();
If #login appears late, this may fail.


page.locator()

Returns a Locator
Locator is “lazy” — it resolves the element when an action happens
Built-in auto waiting
Retries automatically
More reliable for dynamic apps
Recommended modern API

Example:
await page.locator('#login').click();

Playwright waits for:
element to appear
be visible
be actionable
before clicking.

"Q9. How do you handle dropdowns?"

await page.locator('#country').selectOption({
  label: 'India'
});
 or 
await page.selectOption('#country', 'India');

Q13. Difference between toBeVisible() and isVisible()?

| toBeVisible         | isVisible          |
| ------------------- | ------------------ |
| Assertion           | Returns boolean    |
| Auto waits          | No assertion       |
| Used in validations | Used in conditions |


Q17. How do you handle multiple tabs/windows?

const [newPage] = await Promise.all([
  context.waitForEvent('page'),
  page.click('text=Open')
]);

Q19. How do you handle frames?

const frame = page.frameLocator('#frameId');

await frame.locator('#username').fill('admin');


